Democracy.
We in the West make a big mistake to take them for granted.
We do not see democracy as the fragile plant it is in reality, but as the inventory of our society.
We tend to view it as an immutable fact.
We believe that capitalism inevitably leads to democracy.
That's not true.
Lee Kuan Yew of Singapore and his great copycats in Beijing have proven beyond doubt that it is quite possible to have a thriving capitalism and impressive growth, while politics remains completely undemocratic.
In fact, democracy is dwindling with us, in Europe.
Earlier this year, when I represented Greece -- the newly elected Greek government -- I was made unequivocally clear as finance minister in the Eurogroup that our country's democratic process -- our elections -- should not affect the austerity programmes implemented in Greece.
At that moment, I thought that there might not be a better justification for Lee Kuan Yew or the Chinese Communist Party, or some of my defiant friends who repeatedly told me that democracy would be abolished if it changed anything.
At this point, I would like to introduce you to an economic model for a real democracy.
I ask you, together with me, to believe again that Lee Kuan Yew, the Chinese Communist Party and even the Eurogroup succumb to a misconception that we could save ourselves democracy, but that we need a true and defensive democracy.
Because without democracy, our societies are getting meaner, our futures bleak, and our great, new technologies are being wasted.
On the subject of waste, I would like to point out to you an interesting contradiction that is currently threatening our economies.
I call it the "twin summit paradox."
You know a summit. They know and recognize him as the mountain of debt that casts its long shadow over the US, Europe and the whole world.
We all recognize the mountain of debt,
But few recognize his twin.
A mountain of unused cash that belongs to wealthy savers and corporations, but which are too afraid to invest it where it would be productive and could contribute income, with which to pay off the debt pile and also produce all the things that humanity desperately needs, for example, "green" energy.
I'll give them two numbers.
Over the past 3 months, 3.4 trillion dollars have been invested in the US, in England and the eurozone combined, in all the wealth-producing goods, such as industrial facilities, machinery, office buildings, schools, roads, tracks, equipment and so on and so on.
US$3.4 trillion sounds like a lot of money until you compare it to the 5.1 trillion dollars that were lying around in the same countries and our financial institutions at the same time, and did absolutely nothing but inflate the exchanges and drive up real estate prices.
Thus, debt and unproductive capital form the twin summits, which do not compensate themselves by the usual market mechanisms.
The result is stagnant wages, more than a quarter of 25-54 year olds in the US, Japan and Europe unemployed, and consequently low macroeconomic demand, which, as in an endless loop, reinforces investor pessimism, which, fearing low demand, promotes these themselves in which they do not invest. Just like Oedipus's father, who, for fear, the prophecy of the Oracle could come true that his son would kill him when he grows up,
unintentionally brings about the circumstances that cause Oedipus to kill him.
This is my quarrel with capitalism --
his extremely wasteful nature. All the unproductive capital should be used to improve our lives, to further develop human talents and especially to finance all the technologies, "green" technologies that are crucial to saving the earth.
So is democracy the solution?
I think so. But before we continue: What do we mean by democracy?
Aristotle defined democracy as the form of society in which the free and the poor as the majority control the government.
Athenian democracy, of course, ruled out too many --
Women, foreigners, and of course slaves.
However, it would be a mistake to reduce the importance of Athenian democracy because of these exclusions.
The crucial thing about Athenian democracy was and is that it included the working poor, and not only gave them the right to freedom of expression, but is more important and more decisive that it granted them the right to political participation with equal weighting on issues of state concerns.
The Athenian democracy has not lasted long --
Like a candle that shines very brightly, it is also quickly burned out.
However, our liberal democracies today do not have their roots in ancient Athens,
but in the Magna Carta, in the glorious revolution of 1688, even in the American Constitution.
While Athenian democracy focused on the free citizens and strengthened the working poor, our liberal democracy is based on the values of the Magna Carta, which was ultimately a statute for rulers.
Because liberal democracy only came up when a complete separation of politics and business was possible and the democratic process was narrowed down to politics, while the economy -- that is, the world of corporations -- became a democracy-free zone.
In today’s democracies, since the time this separation of politics and business began, a relentless struggle has taken place between the two, gradually subverting and disempowering politics.
Do you wonder why politicians are not the same as before?
It is not because of the degeneration of their DNA.
It's because you can be in government these days and still not in power because power has migrated from politics to the economy and the areas are separate.
I mentioned my quarrels with capitalism.
If you think about it, it is something like a herd of predators that has so sustainably decimated the animals that it feeds on, that it is therefore starving in the end.
It is similar to the economy, which has cannibalized politics to such an extent that it is harming itself by the self-inflicted economic crisis. The power of corporations is growing, political goods are being devalued, inequality is rising, overall economic demand is falling and the managing directors of the corporations are too scared to invest the cash of their companies.
The more successful capitalism drives the "demos" [the people] out of democracy, the higher the twin summits become, and the greater the waste of human labor power and the prosperity of humanity.
If that is true, it is obvious that we must bring politics and the economy back together, and it would be better if the "demos" retain control in the process, as in ancient Athens, apart from the exclusion of slaves, women and foreigners.
This is not a new idea, by the way.
The Marxist left had this idea 100 years ago and it did not go down very well.
The lesson from the debacle of the Soviet Union should be that the working poor regain only by a miracle a position like in ancient Athens, without creating new kinds of brutality and waste.
But there is a solution: to abolish the working poor!
Capitalism does it by replacing low-wage workers with automation and robots.
The problem with this, as long as the economy and politics are separate areas, automation makes the twin summits higher, the waste of sublime, and the social conflicts deeper, just as it will -- very soon, I believe -- come in countries like China.
So we need to reshape the economy and reunite the areas of business and politics, and in doing so, make sure that we democratize the reunified area, otherwise we end up in a pathological surveillance hyperautocracy that makes the film "Matrix" seem like a documentary.
So the question is not whether capitalism will survive the technical achievements it has produced --
the more interesting question is whether capitalism is replaced by a dystopia similar to that in "Matrix" or by something similar to society in "Star Trek," in which machines serve people and people put their energy into the exploration of the universe, or indulge in a high-tech version of the ancient Athenian "Agora," in long conversations, the meaning of life.
I think we can be optimistic.
So what would it take, what might it look like to have this "Star Trek"-like utopia instead of the "Matrix"-like dystopia?
In the practical implementation, I would like to mention you in brief, a few examples.
In the area of companies: Please imagine a capital market in which you earn money while you work and in which your capital follows you from one job to the next, from one company to the next, and the company -- no matter what you work in -- is the property of those who currently work in the company.
Then all incomes come from capital and from proceeds, and the concept of wage labour is completely outdated.
No longer a distinction between those who own the companies, but who do not work in them, and employees who work there, but who do not own the company. No more tug-of-war between capital and labor, no more big gaps between investment and saving, and ultimately no towering twin peaks.
In the field of global political economy: Please imagine briefly that our national currencies would have a free-fluctuating exchange rate, in a universal, global, digital currency issued by the IMF [International Monetary Fund], and the G-20 [Group of 20 largest emerging economies], in the interest of all humanity.
Continue to imagine that all world trade is traded in this currency -- let's call it "the cosmos," in units of "cosmos" -- and each government will pay the sum equivalent to the trade deficit or trade surplus of the respective country into a common fund.
Also imagine that this fund invests in "green" technologies, especially in parts of the world where investment funds are scarce.
This is not a new idea.
It's basically what John Maynard Keynes had suggested in the 1944 Bretton Woods Conference.
The problem was that you didn’t have the technical means to implement it at the time.
Today we have them, especially against the background of a reunified politics and economy.
The world I describe to you is simultaneously libertarian, in which it prefers privileged individuals, and Marxist, because it will have buried the separation of capital and labour in the trash can of history, and Keynesian, global Keynesian.
But above all else, it's a world where we can imagine a real democracy.
Will we wake up in such a world
Or will we sink into a "matrix"-- similar dystopia?
The answer depends on how we decide together politically.
It's in our hands, and we're better off doing it democratically.
Thank you. Thank you.
