Even the data most accomplished companies like Amazon and Google sometimes misunderstand something.
Despite all these errors, data is increasingly pouring into decisions of life -- in the workplace, in law enforcement, in medicine.
So we should make sure that data is helpful.
I also know a lot of difficulties with data. I work in computer-aided genetics -- an area where some very smart people use unimaginably a lot of data to make serious decisions, like the decision for cancer therapy
or the development of a drug. Over the years, I have recognized some patterns about the difference between successful decisions based on data and not successful decisions. This pattern should be spread.
If you ever have to solve a complex problem, you mainly do two things:
First, break this problem down into its items so you can analyze the items; secondly, you reassemble the items to make a decision.
Sometimes you have to do this several times, but it's always two things: take apart and put it back together.
And now the most important thing: data and data analysis are only good for the first part.
Data and data analysis, no matter how powerful, can only help to break down a problem and understand its parts.
They are not suitable for reassembling the parts and then coming to a decision.
There is another tool for this and we all have it: our brains.
If there is something where the brain is good at, it is to put parts and pieces back together, even if the information is incomplete, to then make a good decision -- especially if it's an expert's brain.
That's why, I think, Netflix was so successful because they used data and mind where they belong in the process.
They use data to better understand their audience what they would not otherwise have been capable of. But the decision of how to take all these parts back together and turn it into a show like "House of Cards" didn't stand in the data.
